<P>THOUGH the Reader in many Hi&s;tories is o|bliged to dige&s;t much more unaccountable Ap|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">arances than this of Mr. <HI>We&s;tern,</HI> without any Sa|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="2 letters">sfaction at all; yet as we dearly love to oblige him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">henever it is in our Power, we &s;hall now proceed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;hew by what Method the Squire di&s;covered where <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">s Daughter was.</P>
<P>In the third Chapter then of the preceding Book, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">e gave a Hint (for it is not our Cu&s;tom to unfold at <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">y Time more than is nece&s;&s;ary for the Occa&s;ion) <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="2 letters">at Mrs. <HI>Fitzpatrick,</HI> who was very de&s;irous of re|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="2 letters">nciling her&s;elf to her Uncle and Aunt <HI>We&s;tern,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">ought &s;he had a probable Opportunity by the Service <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter"> pre&s;erving <HI>Sophia</HI> from committing the &s;ame Crime <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">hich had drawn on her&s;elf the Anger of her Family.
